<HEADLINE>
<P>
JAZZ ALBUM REVIEWS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DON HECKMAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 ** David Benoit/Russ Freeman, "The Benoit/Freeman Project," GRP. There's a lot 
more pop than jazz in this musical joining of two well-known contemporary 
stylists, who play piano and guitar, respectively.With the exception of one or 
two feisty works such as "Swept Away" and "Smartypants," most of the originals 
float through space so easily that they quickly slip into the category of 
pleasant background music. Ironically, it is two vocal numbers -- sung by Phil 
Perry and Vesta ("After the Love Has Gone") and Kenny Loggins ("When She 
Believed in Me") -- that give the album its most intriguing moments. 
</P>
<P>
 New albums are rated on a scale of one star (poor), two stars (fair), three 
stars (good) and four stars (excellent). DON HECKMAN 
</P>
