648 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
GO WITH THE FLOW; SUSAN CLOVER'S CURRENT WORK OFFERS TRANQUIL AND SENSUAL 
SCENES OF PEOPLE IN WATER, REPRESENTATIVE OF THE CLASSIC CALIFORNIA LIFESTYLE. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By NANCY KAPITANOFF, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES; Nancy Kapitanoff writes regularly 
about art for The Times. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Fires, floods and earthquakes have not stopped Susan Clover of Seal Beach from 
painting scenes that convey the joys of living in Southern California. 
</P>
<P>
 Her latest series of 12 paintings at Orlando Gallery carry on a theme that has 
captivated her for more than 20 years: figures in delightful water 
environments. 
</P>
<P>
 "I love water, the way it splashes and sparkles, the way light plays on it. 
Water is a very sensual symbol," Clover said. Being in water "is an experience 
that everyone has had, so I don't feel like I'm painting something that isn't 
understood." 
</P>
<P>
 Using her sister, her son and daughter and their friends as models, Clover 
photographs them sunbathing, walking along the beach, lollygagging in the surf, 
dipping a foot into a secluded stream. With a color pallet that conveys the 
coolness of late-afternoon ocean breezes and the intensity of an atmosphere 
drenched in sunlight, she turns those photographs into richly textured, vibrant 
paintings of good-looking people in the most seductive of California 
environments. 
</P>
<P>
 "She has a luminosity to her work and an inner light that she creates through 
the use of color," gallery director Bob Gino said. "It's just not water per se; 
it's what the water says to her. There's where she creates the sensuality in 
the water." 
</P>
<P>
 "The water reflects back into the skin," Clover said. To re-create the effects 
of light and shadow on the body, she "uses more color in skin," Gino said, than 
any other artist he knows. 
</P>
<P>
 Because of its translucence and color, a painting such as "Water and Light" 
seems almost three-dimensional to Gino. In this picture, two women float about. 
"She creates a roundness in the body -- what the body is all about. It's like 
you can go in and around them," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Clover strives to create "an environment you feel you can walk into. When you 
paint, you're not painting some thing. You're painting color and shape and 
direction." 
</P>
<P>
 Clover works indoors but under light that duplicates sunlight. Using brushes, 
a pallet knife and her fingers for blending, she does strokes that are loose 
and free. Stand close to her paintings and they appear more like abstract 
compositions. Move back, and the bold, realist images emerge. 
</P>
<P>
 In "Wading at Jetty," we see a man and woman from the back. She wears a bright 
print skirt in primary colors, but we can also see the shadow of her leg 
underneath the skirt. We seem to be following the couple as they pass the jetty 
rocks covered with a rich, green moss. The soft color of the sky and water 
indicates the sun is on its way down. "She transports you to tranquillity," 
Gino said. 
</P>
<P>
 In "Water Reflections," a young woman nonchalantly plays with her long, wet 
hair after a dip. The vividness of the image stirs memories of how content one 
can feel after an exhilarating swim. The attention to details, such as the 
numerous appealing rings on the woman's fingers, enhances the personal nature 
of the picture. 
</P>
<P>
 Clover's sister, artist Joyce Wisdom, is at the center of "Green 
Fern-Topanga." Wearing a big sun hat and a sheer print skirt, she sits by a 
stream soaking up the lush surroundings. Clover prefers to paint people she 
knows "because I have an emotional response to the people I know. There's 
detachment there if you don't know" your subjects, she said. 
</P>
<P>
 She also enjoys depicting the intimacy of couples as in "Cozy," where a man 
hugs a woman close. "It puts a sexual play between the two people. You 
introduce another factor," she said. 
</P>
<P>
 Clover, a Los Angeles native, said she will continue to paint the people most 
dear to her living the California lifestyle she finds so compelling. "I see the 
beauty of what's around me all the time," she said. Where and When 
</P>
<P>
 What: "Susan Clover: Paintings." 
</P>
<P>
 Location: Orlando Gallery, 14553 Ventura Blvd., Sherman Oaks. 
</P>
<P>
 Hours: 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. Tuesdays through Saturdays. Ends April 29. 
</P>
<P>
 Call: (818) 789-6012. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Art Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA042294-0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 034562 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
April 22, 1994, Friday, Valley Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Valley Life; Page 8 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
