<P>
N. KOREA OFFERS PEEK AT NUCLEAR EFFORT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 North Korea on Thursday offered the world a look at key evidence in a dispute 
over its alleged secret atomic bomb project, inviting U.N. experts to watch as 
its main nuclear reactor is refueled. 
</P>
<P>
 International Atomic Energy Agency spokesman David Kyd said inspection of the 
Yongbyon reactor's exhausted fuel core is vital to try to clear up allegations 
that Pyongyang is developing nuclear weapons. 
</P>
<P>
 He said the U.N. agency responded positively to the new North Korean offer 
and, provided other elements of a fresh IAEA inspection could be agreed upon, a 
new expert mission would leave for Yongbyon next week. 
</P>
<P>
 The presence of inspectors is necessary "to verify that there has been no 
diversion of nuclear materials," Kyd said. He cautioned that final, complete 
details of the new offer still must be settled. 
</P>
