<HEADLINE>
<P>
SPEAKING UP : A LOOK AT NOTEWORTHY ADDRESSES IN THE SOUTHLAND.  
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Santa Monica City Councilman Tony Vasquez spoke Tuesday at Loyola Marymount 
University on Westside Latinos and the Political Landscape of Los Angeles 
County. His remarks were sponsored by the Loyola Marymount University Chicano 
studies department. From his address: 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 On Latino Role Models 
</P>
<P>
 "When I received the (invitation to speak) it was kind of refreshing that 
somebody was taking interest in the Westside, because the focus has always been 
on the Eastside. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 "I was actually raised on the Westside, between Santa Monica, West Los Angeles 
and Mar Vista. So for me growing up as a kid there weren't really role models. 
</P>
<P>
 "When you're sitting in a classroom like this and you're not looking at 
somebody that reflects you and your history and your culture, it's very 
difficult for you or your peers to really feel like there's some hope and a 
chance for you to be in the driver's seat. 
</P>
<P>
 "Growing up here, I didn't have a Chicano, Latino, Central American or South 
American teacher until I got to college. I went through elementary school, 
middle school, high school and even part of my community college days. . . . 
The majority of the folks on the Westside have never seen a Latino professor or 
teacher. Now it's starting to break through but it's still a small percentage. 
. . . 
</P>
<P>
 "I think it's more difficult for people of color, specifically Latinos, these 
last 20 years on the Westside than it's been on the Eastside. Because on the 
Eastside there are some role models. Garfield High School is a good example, 
has always had a good presence. Probably not enough in terms of the 
representation that exists in that community, but there's been a presence 
nevertheless. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 "The school I taught (at) was actually in unincorporated East Los Angeles. 
These were elementary school kids, third-graders. I happened to be their first 
male Latino at that particular school. They'd had other Mexican American and 
Central American teachers but they'd never had a male. So that was kind of a 
culture shock, I think, for a lot of the kids." On Coalition-Building 
</P>
<P>
 "(Latinos) are going to have the largest group to be coming of age to vote and 
hopefully get involved in civic activities within the community. It's key for 
you as students to look at that and begin to figure out where you want to be in 
that picture and what your role is going to be. . . . We realized that for us 
we needed to get and gain some political power. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 "The way it came was through coalition-building. Santa Monica has about 93,000 
people . . . according to the 1990 census. Latinos make up about 13% to 14%. Of 
that number, only about 2% are registered and eligible to vote. So there's no 
way, even if you had everybody voting for you in the Latino community, you're 
going to win an election in Santa Monica.  
</P>
<P>
 "One of the things you need to understand is that when you're dealing with 
coalition-building, it's not just about your little niche. It's talking about 
the wealth and the good of all the people in the community. 
</P>
<P>
 "You need to coalesce with other groups. So you need to identify those other 
groups, whether it's the African American community, the Asian Pacific 
community or the Anglo population. Find the commonalities that you can agree 
upon and then those things that you disagree on and agree to disagree. And 
that's OK. . . . We agree to disagree, we find the commonality and we move 
forward.  
</P>
<P>
 "But without Latinos, specifically on the Westside and in Greater Los Angeles, 
sitting at the table, whether it's on the city council level or at the school 
board level, we're not part of the process. Particular positions and issues as 
they affect our community are not even being heard. . . . We need professional 
role models, at all levels. Unless we're sitting at the table doing that, it's 
not going to happen. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 "For the longest time, people have always identified, once again, the Eastside 
and other parts of Los Angeles, and not the Westside, as (having) a large 
number of Latinos. But it doesn't mean a whole lot if we're not taking an 
active role. Looking Ahead 
</P>
<P>
 * Monday: James Fallows, Washington editor of the Atlantic Monthly, will speak 
about "Can America Avoid a Collision with East Asia?" at the Biltmore Hotel, 
noon. His remarks will be sponsored by the Los Angeles World Affairs Council in 
cooperation with the Japan America Society. Call (213) 628-2333. 
</P>
</TEXT>
