<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: LOS ANGELES; ARAB 
GROUP'S DIRECTOR QUITS TO RETURN TO MIDEAST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Southern California regional director of the American-Arab 
Anti-Discrimination Committee, Nazih Bayda, has resigned for personal reasons, 
and plans to resume his career as a petroleum engineer by taking a job in the 
Persian Gulf sheikdom of Abu Dhabi, it was announced Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
 Bayda, 35, played a key role in protesting interviews of prominent Arab 
Americans by the FBI at the beginning of the Gulf War in 1991.A previous 
regional director of the Anti-Discrimination Committee, Alex Odeh, was murdered 
1985. 
</P>
<P>
 Bayda said that damage at his San Fernando Valley home from the Jan. 17 
earthquake had led to his family's decision to leave Los Angeles. His 
performance at the Anti-Discrimination Committee, where he had been regional 
director for six years, won praise from Don Boustany, the group's Los 
Angeles-area president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
