<HEADLINE>
<P>
RAIDERS' KELLY VOWS NOT TO RE-SIGN FOR LESS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LONNIE WHITE, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Raiders' plan was simple when they waived Joe Kelly, their starting middle 
linebacker, earlier in the week. 
</P>
<P>
 Cut him now and hope to re-sign him before training camp for less money.Around 
the NFL, that's a common practice these salary-cap days. 
</P>
<P>
 In this case, however, this move might backfire. Kelly, who finished second in 
tackles for the Raiders last season, says he will not return. 
</P>
<P>
 "I don't need to have 15 teams knocking on my door, all I need is one to give 
me a shot," he said. "If I have to play for less anywhere, it sure will not be 
with the Raiders." 
</P>
<P>
 Kelly signed as a free agent with the Raiders last season after two seasons 
with the New York Jets and three with the Cincinnati Bengals. 
</P>
<P>
 After signing two high-priced free agents, offensive guard Kevin Gogan from 
Dallas and cornerback Albert Lewis from Kansas City, and re-signing wide 
receiver Tim Brown, the Raiders released Kelly, who earned $600,000 last 
season, to make room under the cap before Sunday's NFL draft. 
</P>
<P>
 Kelly could have made $950,000 in salary, bonuses and incentives next season. 
</P>
<P>
 Without Kelly, the Raiders would have only inexperienced Greg Biekert at 
middle linebacker. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA042294-0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 034800 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
April 22, 1994, Friday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 3; Column 1; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
389 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
FORMER COWBOY COACH JOHNSON REELS IN TV JOB 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LARRY STEWART, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Jimmy Johnson, saying a coach can only fish for so long, accepted a job 
Thursday as a studio commentator for the Fox network. 
</P>
<P>
 He will work with Terry Bradshaw, Howie Long and a yet-to-be-named host on 
Fox's Los Angeles-based one-hour shows before NFL games on Sunday mornings. 
</P>
<P>
 Asked if the television job was for one year only, the former Dallas Cowboy 
coach said, "There's a possibility, a strong possibility, that I'll do it for 
more than one year, but I'm also not closing the door on coaching." 
</P>
<P>
 According to industry sources, he will make $650,000 from Fox, and $250,000 
more if, as expected, he signs to work for HBO as well. 
</P>
<P>
 With HBO, Johnson would be part of the pay-cable network's critically 
acclaimed Thursday night show, "Inside the NFL." 
</P>
<P>
 "There's a strong possibility an announcement (regarding HBO) will be 
forthcoming in the next few days," Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
 Ross Greenburg, the executive producer for HBO sports, concurred and also took 
a shot at Fox for "trying to blow us out of the water." 
</P>
<P>
 "They tried to demand exclusivity, and I didn't appreciate that, to be honest 
about it," Greenburg said. "But Jimmy was professional enough to stand up for 
us." 
</P>
<P>
 ESPN and Turner Broadcasting also made bids for Johnson's expertise as a 
studio analyst, but because they are both cable entities, he couldn't also have 
worked for HBO had he chosen one of them. 
</P>
<P>
 Ed Goren, the executive producer for Fox sports, said a host for the network's 
NFL pregame show won't be announced for a while. 
</P>
<P>
 Greg Gumbel, whose CBS contract expires this fall, is considered the 
front-runner. Roy Firestone is also a candidate. 
</P>
<P>
 Goren said that because the Fox show will be one hour, there will be plenty of 
room for everyone. 
</P>
<P>
 Johnson said he got to know Bradshaw when he was an assistant coach at 
Louisiana Tech. 
</P>
<P>
 Johnson said he coached Long in the 1979 Blue-Gray game. 
</P>
<P>
 Johnson, who has been doing coach's shows for about 25 years, said that with 
Fox he hopes to add "some in-house knowledge and convey that to the viewer." 
</P>
<P>
 Will he be critical? 
</P>
<P>
 "If you'll check the record, I was not that reserved when someone was paying 
my salary, and I don't think I'll be that reserved now." 
</P>
<P>
 He also said, "I'm not going to go out of my way to take a shot at anyone, but 
I'm not going to change my personality. I'm just going to give opinions." 
</P>
</TEXT>
