<HEADLINE>
<P>
ROY SIDELINED WITH APPENDICITIS AS CANADIENS ROUTED BY BRUINS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Montreal Canadiens received a blow to their defense of the Stanley Cup 
title when goalie Patrick Roy, the key in last year's success, was hospitalized 
Thursday because of appendicitis that might require surgery. 
</P>
<P>
 Without Roy, the Canadiens gave up three first-period goals behind Ron Tugnutt 
as the Boston Bruins cruised to 6-3 victory at Montreal to take a 2-1 lead in 
the best-of-seven series. 
</P>
<P>
 The Bruins did not waste time in taking advantage of Roy's absence as Tugnutt 
allowed five of Boston's first 13 shots into the net, including two from long 
range. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm obviously very disappointed with how I performed," said Tugnutt, who was 
acquired from the Mighty Ducks in February. "I'll take my part of the blame." 
</P>
<P>
 Roy, 28, could return for Game 4 on Saturday if it is determined today he does 
not require surgery. 
</P>
<P>
 An operation would sideline him for 10 to 14 days, meaning he would not return 
until the second round of playoffs -- if Montreal advances past Boston. 
</P>
<P>
 "If he recovers, he can play as soon as he gets a few meals under his belt," 
said Douglas Kinnear, the Montreal team physician. 
</P>
