<LENGTH>
<P>
122 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: INTERNATIONAL TRADE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Chris Woodyard, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Water Purifier: OffShore Marine Laboratories in Laguna Hills has shipped one 
of its water-purification units to the island of Truk in Micronesia, where it 
will be installed in a hotel. 
</P>
<P>
 The unit is capable of producing 25,000 gallons of fresh water a day for 
guests at the Continental Hotel on the island, a World War II battle site that 
has become popular with recreational divers who explore the coral reefs. 
</P>
<P>
 The unit is easy to transport because it comes in the same configuration as a 
20-foot ocean shipping container. It is valued at $150,000, said OffShore 
President Thomas Duncan.  
</P>
<P>
 It purifies water through a reverse-osmosis system, forcing salt water through 
a membrane to filter out salt and other impurities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
